I recently made a comic complaining that NASA refuses to listen to my good ideas for improving the Solar System (xkcd.com/2750).

To my delight, NASA’s Science Mission Directorate has sent me an actual expert panel evaluation of my “flatten the planets” proposal! Sadly, they decided not to fund it.

(6/6) Thanks to everyone who sent in suggestions! I’ll post an update if I ever figure out anything more. In the meantime, if you like these kinds of lost-media mysteries, I recommend the Reply All episode The Case of the Missing Hit: gimletmedia.com/shows/reply-...

(5/6) I think the most likely explanation has to be that my memory is unreliable, it was one of those two songs, and the reddit poster is conflating it with a different song/video. But deep down I suspect that it’s neither of those—it’s a real lost song and I’ll recognize it if I ever hear it again.

(4/6) Neither of these sounds quite right to me. I remember the song having a stomping/clapping beat and a vocal-heavy Spice Girls-ish vibe. I think I would have remembered the Sinai Rose guitar or the kids voices. (And neither match the reddit poster’s video/lyrics.) www.reddit.com/r/tipofmyton...

(3/6) Thank you to everyone who dug up so many candidates! One possibility is Isabella Barrett’s “LOL Remix (feat. Eden Wood)”, a 2013 song by a pair of children: open.spotify.com/track/7xwwYQ...

The other best match is Sinai Rose's “L.O.L.” from Kidz Bop 2009: www.youtube.com/watch?v=bITR...

(2/6) First, some details: I heard it circa 2010-14. It was unambiguously an internet reference, not misheard syllables. It wasn’t Mabel or Ashlee Simpson. The chorus was “ell oh ell oh ell...” repeated for I think 15 syllables. Here’s my memory of the cadence of the chorus: xkcd.com/static/lol.m4a
(1/6) An update on the LOL song mystery: No definite resolution, but here's a brief thread with some extra information and a few strong possibilities.

I remember it being a bit slower and more even, with more voices, with the LOLOLO… being 15 syllables long (with that line possibly repeated several times). But this might just turn out to be a case of memory being unsatisfyingly unreliable.

Unfortunately, I don’t recall ANY of the other lyrics, except that something in them made it clear to me that LOL was intentionally an internet reference and not just nonsense syllables. But the number of LOLs and the other things she describes about the sound of the song definitely match my memory.

This is by FAR the closest match anyone has suggested. Some of it doesn’t sound right (guitar, cadence/rhythm of the LOLs, the voice(s), the other lyrics), but it’s honestly possible that my memory has just distorted it over time, and the reddit poster is mixing it up with a different song. Hmm...
Good song but sadly no! The LOL in the one me and the reddit poster remember repeats unbroken for I think 15 syllables. "LOLOLOLOLOLOLOL."
The latter. The chorus was “Ell oh ell oh ell oh ell oh ell oh ell oh ell oh ell.” (Possibly minus the last “oh ell”—I think it was 15 syllables, but it might have been 13.)

MYSTERY: I was driving in the woods one night with the radio on scan, and a song came on whose chorus was women rhythmically chanting “LOLOLOL.” I've searched for years and found nothing…except ONE reddit post from 2016 describing the exact same song: www.reddit.com/r/tipofmyton...

Individual users can change their settings to not see my replies, of course (“only show replies from people I follow”) but since most people won’t do that, I have to assume that any reply I send is effectively getting reposted to my main feed for most people.

I avoid replying much because of how the “show replies with >X likes” setting works for high-follower accounts. Users who have a low threshold see my replies, then their likes quickly push it over the threshold for others.
